{{italic title}}
{{for|the painting with the same name by [[Peter Paul Rubens]]|Perseus Freeing Andromeda (Rubens)}}
[[File:Piero di Cosimo - Liberazione di Andromeda - Google Art Project.jpg|300px|thumb|Piero di Cosimo, ''Perseus Freeing Andromeda'', 1510 or 1513. 70 cm × 123 cm (28 in × 48 in). Uffizi, Florence]]

'''''Perseus Freeing Andromeda''''' is a painting by the [[Italy|Italian]] [[Renaissance]] painter [[Piero di Cosimo]], c. executed in 1510 or 1513<ref name="f202">Fossi, 202</ref> It is housed in the [[Uffizi Gallery]] of [[Florence]], [[Italy]].

The painting is mentioned in 1568 by [[Giorgio Vasari]], who states that it was commissioned by [[Filippo Strozzi the Elder]], and gifted by Giovanni Battista Strozzi to a member of [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany|Cosimo I de' Medici]]'s personnel. 

The work shows the [[Greek mythology|mythological hero]] [[Perseus (mythology)|Perseus]] killing the monster who had entrapped [[Andromeda (mythology)|Andromeda]]. Piero gave a great deal of attention to the background, perhaps inspired to the contemporary Flemish school:<ref name="f202"/> details include   the two characters with a [[turban]] on the left, the very detailed painting of the water on the shore, and the fantastic musical instruments.

